This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with the development of end-to-end multimodal SDS (Spoken Dialog Systems) that can communicate with users in natural language about the real dynamic audio-visual sensory world around us. The paper also explores the role of 'topics' as the context of the conversation, which is a key aspect of natural language processing. 

The paper also involves the use of visual grounding techniques and audio understanding, which suggests that it could also belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision). 

Additionally, the paper involves the use of audio classification ConvNet, AclNet, which suggests that it could belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SD (Sound). 

The paper also involves the use of machine learning techniques to enable machines to understand shared semantic concepts, which suggests that it could belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

Finally, the paper involves the development and testing of models, which suggests that it could belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
